  "prompt": "I just bought an Activa 110 cc bike and technicians have advised me against riding it above 40 kmph until the first 750 km. Why is that so?",
  "response": "The recommendation to ride a new motorcycle or scooter at lower speeds during the initial break-in period (usually the first 500-1000 km) is based on several important mechanical considerations:\n\n1. Engine Wear-In\n- New engine parts have microscopic irregularities that need to gradually smooth out\n- Riding at moderate speeds allows components to settle and wear evenly\n- Helps establish proper piston ring sealing and reduces friction\n\n2. Lubrication\n- New engines need time for oil to properly coat and lubricate all moving parts\n- Lower speeds help distribute lubricants more effectively\n- Prevents premature wear of critical engine components\n\n3. Thermal Adjustment\n- Allows different metal parts to expand and contract uniformly\n- Prevents potential warping or uneven wear of engine components\n- Helps establish proper thermal characteristics\n\n4. Reduced Mechanical Stress\n- Lower speeds mean less mechanical stress on new engine parts\n- Prevents potential microscopic damage during initial operation\n- Helps components adjust to working conditions gradually\n\n5. Optimal Performance\n- Following manufacturer's break-in guidelines ensures long-term engine reliability\n- Contributes to better overall performance and longevity\n- Helps maintain warranty conditions\n\nAfter the recommended break-in period, you can gradually increase speed and load on the engine.",
